
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    `bitmap` yek dastoor baraye tabdil kardan aks-ha ya font-ha be formate bitmap dar Unix/Linux ast. Bitmap yek model-e tasviri ast ke tasvir ra be soorate yek shabake az noghte-ha (pixel-ha) zakhire mikonad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `bitmap -f <fontfile>` --> 🔤 Tabdil font be format bitmap.
    🔹 `bitmap -g <geometry>` --> 📐 Tayin andaze-ye tasvir bitmap. Masalan: 64x64
    🔹 `bitmap -n <name>` --> 🏷️ Gozashtan yek esm baraye tasvir.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ bitmap -f myfont.pcf > myfont.bitmap

    🔹 Tabdil font `myfont.pcf` be format bitmap va zakhireh dar file `myfont.bitmap`.

    $ bitmap -g 32x32 -n myicon < input.xpm > output.bitmap

    🔹 Tabdil file `input.xpm` be yek bitmap ba andazeye 32x32 va name `myicon`.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ bitmap -f fixed > fixed.bitmap

    🔹 Tabdil font pishfarz "fixed" be format bitmap va zakhireh dar file `fixed.bitmap`. In dastoor font system ra be yek file bitmap tabdil mikonad ke mishe dar barname-ha azash estefade kard.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    `bitmap` is a command to convert images or fonts to bitmap format in Unix/Linux systems. A bitmap is a digital image format that stores images as a grid of individual pixels.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `bitmap -f <fontfile>` --> 🔤 Convert a font to bitmap format.
    🔹 `bitmap -g <geometry>` --> 📐 Specify the dimensions (geometry) of the bitmap image. Example: 64x64
    🔹 `bitmap -n <name>` --> 🏷️ Assign a name to the image.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ bitmap -f myfont.pcf > myfont.bitmap

    🔹 Convert the font `myfont.pcf` to bitmap format and save it in the file `myfont.bitmap`.

    $ bitmap -g 32x32 -n myicon < input.xpm > output.bitmap

    🔹 Convert the `input.xpm` file to a bitmap with dimensions 32x32 and the name `myicon`.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ bitmap -f fixed > fixed.bitmap

    🔹 Convert the default "fixed" font to bitmap format and save it in the file `fixed.bitmap`. This command turns a font system into a bitmap file that can then be used in programs.
